	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Chinese fisheries companies embrace the African seafood market</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 January 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>China Fishery Group is a major fishing company specialised in trawling for small pelagics and fishmeal/fish oil production. In October 2010 it started fishing for species such as horse mackerel and sardines in waters off Mauritania, and hopes that Africa will not only be a source of fish but also a new market. The company’s managing director hopes that the continent could account for 20-30% of total sales in 3-4 years from less than 7% currently.</p><p>China Fishery Group expects to invest more in Africa by opening fish-processing factories in Mauritania, and is on the lookout for possible acquisitions that would help it expand its fishing fleet. Currently the group operates a fleet of about 80 fishing vessels and supplies the bulk of its catch to China. By expanding into Mauritania, it obtains access to new fishing grounds where its vessels can be used more efficiently during the off-peak season in the South Pacific, without incurring too much additional investment.</p><p>China Fishery Group also benefits from its links to the parent Pacific Andes Group, another fishing giant. Following an agreement with a Mauritanian fishing agent, Pacific Andes has sent two of its freezer trawlers to Mauritania with the possibility of increasing the number of vessels to five. It is understood that Pacific Andes is also sending its factory ship <i>La Fayette</i>&nbsp;to be supplied by its own refrigerated seawater trawlers as well as others from Europe, including Ireland and Scotland.</p><p>The managing director of Pacific Andes highlighted that the firm had decided to expand heavily into African catching and distribution, because they believed that Africa had even greater growth potential than China. Mauritania is also close to major African markets for frozen small pelagic fish, such as Ghana or Nigeria.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
‘China Fishery embraces African seafood and market’ FIS World News, 26 November 2010<br/>

<a href="http://fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?monthyear=&amp;day=26&amp;id=39425&amp;l=e&amp;special=0&amp;ndb=0" target="_self">http://fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?monthyear=&amp;day=26&amp;id=...</a><br/>
China Fishery Group website, financial information, prospects and outlook for 2010<br/>
<a href="http://www.chinafisherygroup.com/news_events.html" target="_self">http://www.chinafisherygroup.com/news_events.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Small pelagics, despite having a relatively low commercial value on international markets, are a strategic resource for many ACP countries. Not only do they play a central role in livelihood and food security, offering local populations a high-quality source of protein at affordable prices, but they also provide the basic food for many commercial species, like tuna and other top carnivores, sold on lucrative markets such as the EU. What seems to be of interest for new players, whether from China, EU or elsewhere, is primarily to secure access to these strategic resources for their fleets. The means used by Chinese firms to secure such access has been to invest locally in processing units, particularly for fishmeal. For its part, the EU continues to favour paying for access through FPAs. But in both cases, potential gains for ACP countries, in terms of jobs created, revenue from trade or access fees received, will only be sustainable if the exploitation of small pelagics is kept at sustainable levels so as to maintain their contribution to food security, whilst not jeopardising the prospects of high-value commercial species that feed on them.</p>
		</div>
		
